result.execSummary:
Jonathan Marshall Gause was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Jonathan Marshall Gause was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Letter to Governor mailed w/certified copy of Waiver of Extradition and Florida Warrant
Recitals and Waiver of Extradition Pursuant to 976.03 Wis Stats/s/TBE

12:59 PM Defendant Jonathan Marshall Gause in court.  Attorney Jedidiah J Dodge in court for State of Wisconsin. Atty Maxwell Bergner appears for the defendant.
Atty Dodge states that there is some waiver paperwork not yet completed.
Court questions Atty Bergner.
Atty Dodge states the facts regarding extradition.
Court questions the defendant regarding extradition and his rights in this matter.
Defendant agrees to the extradition.
Defendant waives his right to an extradition hearing.

BY THE COURT:
Defendant is freely, voluntarily, knowingly, and intelligently waiving his right to an extradition hearing.

Atty Dodge provides a copy of the waiver form, first to the defendant to review and sign, and then to the court.
Court signs the order and provides a copy to the defendant.
